{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524199"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13980"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13980"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.75,0.05,0.16,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66796"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52250"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"9136"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22326"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a painful perianal mass. She reports bright red blood on the toilet paper after defecation and significant perianal discomfort when sitting. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation and takes warfarin with a target International Normalised Ratio of 2.0-3.0. She does not take any other regular medications. She reports chronic constipation requiring regular osmotic laxatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a large, irreducible, congested haemorrhoidal mass protruding from the anal canal. Digital rectal examination reveals a single large, thrombosed internal haemorrhoid at the 3 o\u0027clock position.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infrared photocoagulation","Excisional haemorrhoidectomy","Stapled haemorrhoidopexy","Rubber band ligation","Sclerotherapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a grade IV internal haemorrhoid, characterised by permanent prolapse that cannot be reduced manually. The presence of thrombosis, chronic symptoms, and significant impact on quality of life indicates the need for definitive surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcisional haemorrhoidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management option for this patient. While it carries a higher risk of postoperative pain compared to other procedures, it has the lowest recurrence rate and is particularly suitable for large, chronically prolapsed haemorrhoids. The patient\u0027s anticoagulation will need to be managed perioperatively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubber band ligation\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate for grade II and some grade III haemorrhoids but is contraindicated in permanently prolapsed haemorrhoids. It is also relatively contraindicated in anticoagulated patients due to the risk of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfrared photocoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is only suitable for grade I and small grade II haemorrhoids. It would be ineffective for this large, prolapsed haemorrhoid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStapled haemorrhoidopexy\u003C/strong\u003E, while associated with less postoperative pain, has a higher recurrence rate compared to excisional haemorrhoidectomy. It is also less suitable for external components or when there is significant thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is only appropriate for small, non-prolapsed internal haemorrhoids (grade I or II). It would be ineffective for this large, prolapsed haemorrhoid and is relatively contraindicated in anticoagulated patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s chronic constipation should also be addressed as part of the management plan to prevent recurrence. This would include dietary modification, adequate fluid intake, and possibly continued use of osmotic laxatives.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Grade IV haemorrhoids that are permanently prolapsed require surgical management rather than conservative or office-based procedures.","Haemorrhoidectomy is preferred over haemorrhoidopexy for large, chronically prolapsed haemorrhoids due to lower recurrence rates.","Patient factors such as anticoagulation and bowel habits influence the choice of surgical approach for haemorrhoids."],"references":["Mott T, Latimer K, Edwards C. Hemorrhoids: Diagnosis and Treatment Options. American Family Physician [Internet]. 2018 Feb 1;97(3):172\u20139. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29431977/","\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52250"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13980"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20873"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20873"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bCVfKs0YKogAodLgUuqhSi3x0KGr2V.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bCVfKs0YKogAodLgUuqhSi3x0KGr2V.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52250"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T12:57:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T15:05:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66796"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/266"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haemorrhoids","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T12:13:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9136"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"4th degree haemorrhoids","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-15T12:13:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T12:13:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9598"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastrointestinal Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi